14.body:
When using multiple nested loops (including while loops and for loops), you may want to break out of specific loops by labelling them. Note that the label starts with a single quote, but does not end with one. 'outer: loop { 'inner: while true { if condition { break 'outer; } else if other_condition { break 'inner; } }
}

26.body:
In many other languages, a function may throw an exception to the exception handler, which manages the error and decides whether or not to exit the program. In Rust, however, errors are managed with the built-in Result enum, or with panic!ing. Using Result is typically preferable, especially for recoverable errors. Result<T, E> is also generic, and defined as follows, with two generic types (one for valid, and one for error): enum Result<T, E> { // a non-erroneous return value, with user-provided type T Ok(T), // an erroneous return value, with user-provided error type E Err(E),
}

37.body: We're going to keep building on the Pokémon example from the Structs chapter, so it may be helpful to read that one first. As we've seen in the previous chapter, we can tie methods to particular structures, but there isn't traditional inheritance (we can't extend one struct with another). Polymorphism in Rust is a little different, and is done using traits. A trait refers to a set of methods, which should be defined on a number of different structs.

5.body: Variables are defined with the let keyword, and compile-time constants with the const keyword. Variables are traditionally snake_case, and constants are SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE, just like in Python or C. let my_var = 32; const MY_CONST: usize = 32;
5.title: Defining Variables

6.body:
Types can (and may sometimes be required to) be explicitly stated by adding a colon, followed by the type, after the variable name. Note that all consts must be explicitly typed. // the ': u32' explicitly states that my_var has type `u32` (unsigned 32-bit integer)
let my_var: u32 = 32;
6.title: Explicit Types

7.body:
By default, all variables in Rust are immutable, and thus cannot be modified by any means (function calls, operations, etc.). To define a variable as mutable, you must use the mut keyword. Note that consts cannot be mutable, as they are constant. let mut my_var = 32;
my_var += 1;
7.title: Mutability
